FUNCTION IS A BLOCK OF CODE WHICH HAS SOME NAME FOR IDENTIFICATION.


//Function definition
functionName()
{
    code goes here;
}


FUNCTION:
1. Even in the smallest C program there is at least one function called main function.
2. All the function names must be unique.
3. One function name must be main().
4. You can define functions in any sequence.
5. Operating system calls main() function to begin for execution of program.


Function are of two type:
1. PreDefined Functions.
2. UserDefined Functions.


Ways to define a function:
1. Takes Nothing and Returns Nothing. (TNRS)
2. Takes Something and Returns Nothing. (TSRN)
3. Takes Nothing and Returns Something. (TNRS)
4. Takes Something and Returns Something. (TSRS)


1. TNRN
void add()
{
    int a,b;
    printf("ENter two nums: ");
    scanf("%d %d", &a,&b);
    printf("Sum is %d",a+b);
}


2. TSRN
void add(int a, int b)
{
    printf("Sum is %d",a+b);
}


3. TNRS
int add()
{
    int a,b;
    printf("ENter two nums: ");
    scanf("%d %d", &a,&b);
    return a+b;   
}


4. TSRS
int add(int a , int b)
{
    return a+b;
}


Return keyword:
1. It returns value.
2. It returns control to the calling function.
3. We cannot return more than one value using return keyword.
4. We can only use one return keyword in each function.


 
